    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "A student is building a program to show how they spend their time during a 6-hour school day. Right now, they’ve hardcoded the number of total school hours, but they want to update their program to define this as a constant.\r\n\r\n✅ <strong>TO DO #1:</strong> In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">SchoolDay.java</code>, declare and initialize a constant called <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">TOTAL_HOURS</code> to <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">6</code>.\r\n\r\n✅ <strong>TO DO #2:</strong> In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">getSchedule()</code> method, update the code to use the constant instead of the number <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">6</code>.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> Constants should be written in all caps, and declared as <code>public static final</code> at the top of your class.\r\n</div>\r\n",
